T7	p 1478 2060	“The ultrasensitive detection of Xylella fastidiosa has so far made use of molecular detection tests, which target the DNA of the bacterium itself. These analyses, however, require the use of laboratory infrastructures, together with analysis times of at least 3 hours. The innovative electronic platform proposed by the team of Bari researchers would instead allow the detection of the single bacterium in just 30 minutes directly in the field", explains Luisa Torsi of the University of Bari and deputy -President of the Scientific Council of the Cnr who coordinated the research.
